writings by Angela Davis, the George Jackson Brigade, Assata Shakur, the Weather Underground, and others, Dillon shows how these activists were among the first to theorize and make visible the links between conservative "law and order" rhetoric, free market ideology, incarceration, sexism, and the continued legacies of slavery. Dillon theorizes these prisoners and fugitives as queer figures who occupied a unique position from which to highlight how neoliberalism depended upon racialized mass incarceration. In so doing, he articulates a vision of fugitive freedom in which the work of these activists becomes foundational to undoing the reign of the neoliberal-carceral state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAnti-racismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGay activistszUnited States. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeoliberalismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPrisonersxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aProtest movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371892zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371892.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles